{'project_name': 'Amazon Guardians REDD+ Project', 'project_summary': 'The growing threats to the forests of the Peruvian Amazon, such as migratory agriculture, land trafficking illegal logging and illegal gold mining, are causing the alarming degradation of forests; the loss and in some cases the disappearance of the most important flora and fauna in the territory; and the general pollution - deterioration of the country’s most valuable ecosystems. Specifically, illegal (gold) mining have caused tragic damage to part of the Peruvian Amazon. Rivers, streams and soils have been contaminated due to this cause to such degree that it will take many years to remediate and recover -to some extent- their initial state. One of the most affected areas in Peru in terms of deforestation, and specifically due to illegal mining, is the buffer zone of the Tambopata National Reserve and the forests located on the right bank (towards Cusco) of the Interoceanic highway in the region of Madre de Dios.

REDD+ Amazon Guardians purpose is to reduce and avoid deforestation within the conservation, reforestation/afforestation, and ecotourism forest concessions located in the buffer zone of the Tambopata National Reserve and adjacent areas which are highly threatened by illegal mining and traffickers who use these areas for illegal crops. REDD+ Amazon Guardians has been designed and developed with the purpose of protecting these valuable forests and their biodiversity, generating environmental services that allow the capture of CO2 and providing opportunities to improve the quality of life for the communities that live and depend on these areas. 

The project is implemented by Bosques Amazonicos SAC (BAM) in partnership with the concessionaire families in the area, grouped in the Federation of Concessionaires of Madre de Dios, FECOMAD.', 'project_country': 'Peru'}

{'project_name': 'Yunnan Yulong Afforestation Project', 'project_summary': 'Yunnan Yulong Afforestation Project (hereafter refer to as “the project”) is located in Yulong Naxi Autonomous County, Lijiang City, Yunnan Province of China, where 37,400.59 ha (561,008.85 Mu) of the forest was planted on suitable land for forest because of poor sustainable ecological environment and rocky desertification. By checking the afforestation plan, it was confirmed that, a small number of trees have been planted in some project area before the project started, but the coverage rate was extremely low. So, considering the lower forest coverage, Yulong Naxi Autonomous County Forestry and Grassland Bureau determined that the project area is suitable for afforestation after investigation, then the supplementary planting without disturbing the existing trees was approved to increase the vegetative cover. All the trees were planted without disturbing the existing trees in this project, and only the trees actually planted in this project were monitored. The carbon credit of the original trees in the baseline scenario will not be monitored or counted in the actual net GHG removals by sinks. 
The project activity aims to:
-	Sequester greenhouse gas and mitigate climate change;
-	Enhance biodiversity conservation by increasing the connectivity of forests;
-	Improve soil and water conservation in the mountainous region and increase the forest cover;
-	Generate income and job opportunities for local communities.
There is no natural renewal and reforestation before the project, and all sites were suitable land for forest. The main objective species are Pinus yunnanensis (Yunnan Pine) and Picea asperata (Spruce) which are native species according to the baseline survey.
The implementation of the project is expected to reduce the GHG emissions amounting to 22,959,273 tCO2e in 30 years from 16-June-2018 to 15-June-2048, with an average annual GHG emission removal of 765,309 tCO2e.', 'project_state_province': 'Yunnan province', 'project_country': 'China', 'project_latitude': 26.59, 'project_longitude': 99.4}

